# Use LTS / stable versions

- **Default to LTS**: For runtimes and toolchains (Node.js, Python, Java, .NET, Go, Rust, PostgreSQL, etc.) target the active **LTS** or current stable release—never end-of-life or pre-release builds in production code.
- **Pin where it matters**: Lock major versions for languages and frameworks (`engines` in `package.json`, `.nvmrc`, `.python-version`, `pyproject.toml`, `go.mod`, `Cargo.toml`, `Dockerfile` base images). CI should use the same version a developer runs.
- **Libraries**: Prefer the latest stable minor of a maintained major. Avoid `0.x` libraries for core paths unless no alternative exists; never depend on unmaintained packages (no releases for ~12+ months, archived repo, open critical CVEs).
- **No alphas/betas/RCs in main branches**: Pre-release versions belong behind a feature branch or experiment flag, not in `main`/production lockfiles.
- **Upgrade cadence**: When the active LTS changes, plan an upgrade before the previous one hits EOL. Track it as work, don’t silently drift.
- **Verify before bumping**: Read the changelog/migration notes; run the test suite; check transitive deps for compatibility.
- **Security patches**: Apply security releases of the current LTS quickly—do not pin to a vulnerable patch version “for stability.”

```jsonc
// ✅ GOOD: package.json pins to an LTS Node major, current stable libs
{
  "engines": { "node": ">=20.11.0 <21" },
  "dependencies": {
    "express": "^4.19.2",
    "zod": "^3.23.8"
  }
}
```

```text
# ❌ BAD signals
- Node 17 / 19 in CI (non-LTS, EOL)
- "react": "next" or "^0.0.1-alpha.3" in a production app
- A library whose last release was 3+ years ago and has open security issues
```
